deferred-debugger-compiler-two-bodies — Phase 8: compiler two-bodies discipline
================================================================================

See also:
  clautolisp/documentation/clautolisp-debugger-implementation-plan.org (Phase 8)
  clautolisp/documentation/clautolisp-debugger-spec.org (§5, §13)

DEFERRED — gated on the clautolisp compiler-to-CL, which does not yet exist.

Context
-------

clautolisp is currently an interpreter, so the v1 debugger uses the
`*debug-mode*` interpreter instrumentation variant (spec §11.3, §13 "v1").
The full two-bodies discipline (Raskin) with call-site entry-point dispatch
(Fjeld) becomes available only when the compiler-to-CL lands. The debug
protocol (Part III) and all three UIs are UNCHANGED across the migration
(spec §13), so this is purely an instrumentation-backend swap.

Scope (when unblocked)
----------------------

- Emit two CL bodies per AutoLISP defun: `foo/ordinary` (optimised, no poll
  points) and `foo/debug` (instrumented), behind a function-entries vector
  (spec §5.1).
- Disable across-poll-point optimisations in the debug body (spec §5.2): no
  CSE / dead-code elim of sub-form results / LICM / TCO / type-inference
  propagation across poll points.
- Call-site dispatch: ordinary code calls ordinary entry points, debug code
  calls debug entry points; debugging-ness propagates down the call chain
  (spec §5). Emit `function-debug-metadata` from the compiler (spec §7).
- Keep the interpreter available as a fallback (low optimisation /
  macroexpansion debugging).

Acceptance (when unblocked)
---------------------------

- Production (ordinary) code pays zero instrumentation cost; entering a debug
  entry point keeps the whole call chain instrumented; same UI behaviour as
  the interpreter path.
